text:
if when you set a goal and you reach the goal, you feel accomplished, please stop reading...this post is not for you.

this post is for the person that wants one fuggin more!

one more rep.
one more dollar.
one more kiss.
one more dance.
one more hug.
one more award.
one more of every fuggin thing.

this post is not for the champion...this post is for the fuggin master.

i didnt realize i used to live broke thru my early 20's thru my early 30's.

settling for less in every fuggin way. if the goal was 10 bucks, 8 bucks was enough. if the goal was a 100%  90% was enough. i would celebrate enough...instead of pushing past my threshold to hit one fuggin more!!! i would stop short because i knew i was ahead of everyone else. i was fine with winning the race even though i knew i could do fuggin better. again, double mcfugg that with a large coke! 
i would basically settle for less than my best...well you know what settling does? it makes you like that jerk christopher columbus when he landed in the carribean...a settler!!!this jerk thought he was going to india, landed in america and called it the west indies...if that ain't settling...i dont know what is. fugg that.

if you want more in your life you need to push for one more. you need to jump of the damn cliff...you need to be fuggin challenged!!! you gotta jump towards your goals on the count of 3, here are your options:

you can jump on 1
get pushed on 2
or let life push youon 3

what's the troof?

most people say they have a dream (jump on 1) but they're too afraid to move. so they wait until "they're ready" basically jump on 1...becomes jump on 3 years later.

they say "imma jump right on 1"...then a year goes by, "immma jump on 1" yeah right!

now if you dont jump on 1, you can get pushed (challenged) on 2. who is gonna push you??? someone that you trust to challenge you to reach your ultimate destination. someone you know can get you there faster than you would...(i.e. the firestarter)

if you dont jump on 1, or get pushed on 2, life will choose for you on 3. most people die on 3. they wait till it's too late. point: jump muthafuggin now

dm me asap for a challenge! 
#firestarterout
#fuego
#howtobeafirestarter

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
my good friend aaron helped me make this video where i speak about my childhood sexual abuse, the effects it had on my development as a child & teenager & how i have coped vs how i am coping now. i also speak to the benefits of seeking counseling, offer supportive words to other survivors and give information for @calgarycasa which offers (free) counseling to survivors of sexual abuse. they have helped me over the past 12 years until i finally built up the courage to do the right thing (for me) and report my abuse. i have hated this last year and a half of going through the police investigation and the court process but we are closing in on sentencing date and for me this is the light at the end of what has been a very dark tunnel for a very long time. 
thank you to my amazing friend @lee.k.tan for helping me to edit this into the masterpiece it has become. i unfortunately am unable to share the video until after court is finished but i can assure you it is powerful, emotional and inspiring all at once. here's to hoping i can share it with the world sooner than later. 
#ccasa #roadtorecovery #helpingothershelpsyourself #metoo #reportabuse #stopthecycleofabuse

text:
i got flowers today. it wasn't my birthday or any other special day. we had our first argument last night. he said a lot of cruel things that really hurt me. i know he was sorry and didn't mean the things he said. because i got flowers today. 
i got flowers today. it wasn't our anniversary or any other special day. last night, he threw me into a wall and started to choke me. it seemed like a nightmare. i couldn't believe it was real. i woke up this morning sore and bruised all over. i know he must be sorry because he sent me flowers today. 
i got flowers today. it wasn't mother's day or any other special day. last night, he beat me up again. and it was much worse than all other times. if i leave him, what will i do? how will i take care of my kids? what about money? i' m afraid of him and scared to leave. but i know he must be sorry because he sent me flowers today. 
i got flowers today. today was a very special day. it was the day of my funeral. last night he finally killed me. he beat me to death. 
if only i had gathered enough courage and strength to leave him, i would not have gotten flowers today. 
this poem is dedicated to all the victims and survivors of domestic violence. 
you ask, why didn't she leave?

i ask, why did he hit?

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
trauma has a silver lining;
trauma's happen, big t or little t, they change us. the damage gets done. but you can be bitter or better. choose better please, broken people break others, unintentionally but by choosing to ignore or downplay your trauma, your feelings, you spread the pain around. when you actively choose to. face your trauma big or small, you show the greatest bravery and the strongest heart!
when you face your trauma every terrified step forward is bravery!
when you face your trauma your bs tolorance goes way down! your authenticity raises! you can't  allow other people drama to cloud your progress and that's ok! those who can't deal with the reality of your trauma are a) lucky enough to have no personal experience hence no empathy, b) not able to. and that's ok too! not everyone can! or c) couldn't care less or think you deserve it, those people are assholes so be greatful they've shown you their truth and act accordingly.
trauma will teach you what is worth your energy and what makes up fakery in your life, its cleansing. and healing from trauma might be hard work but it feels like victory with every battle won! #nfiniteheart #trauma #ptsd #ptss #cptsd #cptssrecovery #chronicillness #terminalillness #healing #palliativecare #love #caring #counselling #lifecoach #metoo #youvegotthis #consulting

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
â€œany girl hiding behind a mask,

first of all, i understand.

i understand the pain you feel everyday. i understand your fear of admitting how you really feel. i understand how hard it is to wake up and wish you could curl up in a ball and not deal with the world. i understand what it's like to feel alone, despite being surrounded by people who love you. i understand not feeling loved and hating yourself for feeling that way. and most importantly, i understand using a smile so people don't see how you feel.â€ * i have been that girl for years, i have been the girl who makes jokes, who laughs out loud but cries inside, that makes fun of herself rather then facing the demons of her past but a few months ago i made the decision to face the â€œgirl behind the maskâ€. this has been one of the biggest struggles and triumphs in my life, but with love and encouragement, i will some day 100% love that girl. #motivationmonday #nevergiveup #metoo

letâ€™s talk about slut shaming.

actually, letâ€™s talk body-shaming, assumptions, and how some people just suck.

there needs to be unity among women. with a universal understanding that we can show up fully expressed without having to worry about being called a slut, or assuming weâ€™re dumb, or desperate, or â€œasking to be raped.â€ i have been incredibly fortunate to never have been a victim of assault of any kind. but itâ€™s not because of what i wear or donâ€™t wear.

please, judge me based on the words that come out of my mouth and the actions that comprise how i live my life.

but donâ€™t judge me, or any woman, based on what she decides to wear.

go ahead, jan ğŸ™„ clutch your pearls in horror of the â€œsluttyâ€ girl who doesnâ€™t wear pants on instagram. iâ€™ll inspire your daughters some day to become fearless enough to stand up to women like you in defense of women everywhere. youâ€™re ğŸ‘ğŸ½theğŸ‘ğŸ½worstğŸ‘ğŸ½

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,Â wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
my heart is broken, but still somehow full.  thank you stephanie for sharing your story, and for being a voice for all the other women carrying different versions of the same story hidden deep in their hearts.  people wonder why women don't come forward when they get assaulted, but the answer is right here. women almost never get justice, and they are left to find their own path to healing. it's never an easy road, but we all stand together in our collective trauma, because sometimes it's the only thing we can do.
.
.
.
#amightyforce #metoo #neverthelessshepersisted
name: Christine Boomhower

my heart is broken, but still somehow full.  thank you stephanie for sharing your story, and for being a voice for all the other women carrying different versions of the same story hidden deep in their hearts.  people wonder why women do not come forward when they get assaulted, but the answer is right here. women almost never get justice, and they are left to find their own path to healing. it is never an easy road, but we all stand together in our collective trauma, because sometimes it is the only thing we can do.
.
.
.
#amightyforce #metoo #neverthelessshepersisted

text:
â€œwhat if you canâ€™t fight him off because he is bigger than you?â€
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
a fire lit inside me. it was unlike anything i had ever felt before. words began to fly out of my mouth, â€œyou look at me. every single one of you, look straight into my eyes. you are worth fighting for. you fight for your life!â€
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
although i didnâ€™t realize it until hours later that evening, as i processed the events of the day, that moment changed my life forever.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
last july, i had the opportunity to help lead a group of high school students from our church on a mission trip to kenya. we were working with schools in a village there, and from the moment we met these amazing people, they showered us with love and acceptance, unlike anything i've ever experienced before. during our 30 minute bus ride from our hotel to the village on our last day at the schools, we were informed that we needed to lead talks about puberty to the older students, separated by gender.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
as we entered into the room full of 7th and 8th grade girls, i looked around at the bare walls of the classroom and asked god to give me the words to say to these girls.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i started off talking about periods and cramps, but then one of the teachers brought up the subject of guys taking advantage of girls. they asked what to do in a situation like that. in the moment, god gave me 4 things for these girls to do. say no, fight them off, run away and then tell someone.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
that was when one question changed the direction of my life.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
this has become my anthem. fight for your life. i wonder how many #metoo moments could have been avoided if the female knew she had the option to fight? the first instinct is to freeze. we must change that.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
we must also change our instinct to accept things as they are and fall victim to our lives. aside from death, illness or trying to control someone else, you have the power to change whatever is going wrong in your life.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text:
in 2006, tarana burke began using the phrase â€œme tooâ€ to raise awareness of the pervasiveness of sexual abuse and assault in society. in 2017 the movement became viral with the hashtag #metoo and propelled numerous survivors of sexual abuse and assault to come forward with their stories. tarana has been involved in activism since her time in college at auburn university, where she organized press conferences and protests regarding economic and racial justice. she has also been involved and founded organizations that seek to empower young women of color.
thank you, tarana, for speaking up and sharing your story and from that, inspiring thousands of survivors to say me too.

text:
jade jackman
*
we spoke with director jade jackman, newly added to the free the bid database of directors, about her latest work "the future is fluid," created in partnership with #irregularlabs and gucci x chime for change.
*
jade is a 25 year old filmmaker, currently represented by black dog films in the uk. she has worked with platforms such as boiler room, nowness, i-d, vice and the guardian.
*
"this film was made in partnership with #irregularlabs for the re-launch of gucciâ€™s foundation, chime for change. in my signature style, the film blurs the boundary between fact and fiction, while exploring gen-zâ€™s hopes and dreams for gender around the world.
*
this is a way of working that i adopted while shooting, 'calling home,' an experimental documentary that amplifies the voices of young women held in immigration and removal / detention facilities. by borrowing techniques from music videos, fashion films or interesting brand collaborations, i believe that we can engage new audiences and change-up outdated or marginalizing representations.
*
i am committing myself this year to collaborate with a more diverse range of crew and seek out new talent, too. free the bidâ€™s mission in part inspired my all femaleand gnc crew for my latest project, 'station'. in the wake of #metoo, the documentary hybrid takes place in the moment that a woman decides not to report an incident of sexual assault to the police. as survivors and women, we are taking back control of the narrative of sexual violence and, for our contributors, they have said it is empowering to share this with us too."
*
visit freethebid.com to view jadeâ€™s profile and discover the work of many other talented women directors!
*
follow jade on instagram: @jadeshamraeff
*
#freethebid #womendirectors #jadejackman #thefutureisfluid #gendernonconforming #gnc #irregularlabs #gucci #chimeforchange  #director #film #filmmaker #womandirector #femalefilmmaker #femalefilmmakerfriday #femalefilmmakereveryday

text: fear in our body: "by the time we reach adulthood we have difficulty recognizing the sensation of fear in our bodies, not because it is not there, but because it is the foundation for a life-long development of what i call emotional survival adaptations that turn cognitive and behavioral over the course of our developmental years. fear develops often before we are able to remember, or speakâ€”therefore we are unable to put words or cognition to the experience. it is 100% visceral and triggered by sensory input from either outside or inside of our bodies. but as we develop we respond to these triggers in ways that are appropriate for the development of our brains, and later our minds.  by the time we are entering toddlerhood we are capable of understanding basic â€œcause and effectâ€ principle.  much like after a near miss a gazelle will remember where the vulnerable (re dangerous) areas of the plains are, we also can conceptualize how to avoid danger. but in the case of humans, our sense of danger (or a risk to survival) often remains relegated to our perception of disconnection. and when we are very young we canâ€™t conceptualize this danger outside of something we did. the mind of a child is not capable of seeing outside of the self to the parent or caregiver, which is to say that if we spill a glass of milk and the person we are depending on for connection (re survival) becomes angry and loses their temper we are not capable of considering that perhaps they just had a bad day at work and are over-reacting. when we are children, our bodies and minds register a risk of disconnection as caused by something we said or did, and in response we adapt." #trauma #healing #yoga #bodyawareness #mindfulness #community #books #womenempowerment #metoo

text:
jade jackman
*
we spoke with director jade jackman, newly added to the free the bid database of directors, about her latest work "the future is fluid," created in partnership with #irregularlabs and gucci x chime for change.
*
jade is a 25 year old filmmaker, currently represented by black dog films in the uk. she has worked with platforms such as boiler room, nowness, i-d, vice and the guardian.
*
"this film was made in partnership with #irregularlabs for the re-launch of gucciâ€™s foundation, chime for change. in my signature style, the film blurs the boundary between fact and fiction, while exploring gen-zâ€™s hopes and dreams for gender around the world.
*
this is a way of working that i adopted while shooting, 'calling home,' an experimental documentary that amplifies the voices of young women held in immigration and removal / detention facilities. by borrowing techniques from music videos, fashion films or interesting brand collaborations, i believe that we can engage new audiences and change-up outdated or marginalizing representations.
*
i am committing myself this year to collaborate with a more diverse range of crew and seek out new talent, too. free the bidâ€™s mission in part inspired my all femaleand gnc crew for my latest project, 'station'. in the wake of #metoo, the documentary hybrid takes place in the moment that a woman decides not to report an incident of sexual assault to the police. as survivors and women, we are taking back control of the narrative of sexual violence and, for our contributors, they have said it is empowering to share this with us too."
*
visit freethebid.com to view jadeâ€™s profile and discover the work of many other talented women directors!
*
follow jade on instagram: @jadeshamraeff
*

i am committing myself this year to collaborate with a more diverse range of crew and seek out new talent, too. free the bidâ€™s mission in pa inspired my all femaleand gnc crew for my latest project, 'station'. in the wake of  the documentary hybrid takes place in the moment that a woman decides not to repo an incident of sexual assault to the police. as survivors and women, we are taking back control of the narrative of sexual violence and, for our contributors, they have said it is empowering to share this with us too."

text:
according to the national sexual violence resource center * 1 in 5 women and 1 in 71 men will be raped at some point in their lives.
* in the united stares 1 in 3 women and 1 in 6 men experienced some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 51.1% of female victims of rape reported being raped by an intimate partner and 40.8% by an acquaintance.
* 52.4% of male victims report being raped by an acquaintance and 15.1% by a stranger.
* 49.5% of multiracial women and over 45% of american indian/alaska native women were subjected to some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 91% of victims of rape and sexual assault are female, and 9% are male * in 8 out of 10 cases of rape, the victim knew the perpetrator.
* 8% of rapes occur while the victim is at work. 
the problem of sexual violence runs rampant, and yet rape is the most under-reported crime; 63% of sexual assaults are not reported to police. of the remaining 37% that are reported less than 10% are instances of false reporting. the facts are clear, and still the culture that would rather victims of sexually based crimes remain silent prevails. 
join rebecca macceile as she throws off the shackles of silence and raises her voice. turquoise boot straps: a survivorâ€™s thoughts provides a glimpse into her journey of self discovery while tackling many controversial topics at the height of the metoo era.

text:
"collective action and shared responsibility for driving gender parity is what makes international women's day successful"

did you know?
"international women's day (march ğŸ˜ is a global day celebrating the social, economic, cultural and political achievements of women. the day also marks a call to action for accelerating gender parity. international women's day (iwd) has occurred for well over a century, with the first march 8 iwd gathering supported by over a million people in austria, denmark, germany and switzerland. prior to this the socialist party of america, united kingdom's suffragists and suffragettes, and further groups campaigned for women equality. today, iwd belongs to all groups collectively everywhere. iwd is not country, group or organisation specific. make iwd your day! - everyday!

how are will you be celebrating international women's day this year? get involved and/or join us:

text:
itâ€™s my birthday week so i kinda donâ€™t know how to ackkkk. ğŸ˜ğŸ˜‚ birthdays have always been a huge thing for me. iâ€™m the awkward person that always does a bday countdown and wonâ€™t let anyone around me forget that a national holiday is about to arrive! 
though birthdays have been special to me, iâ€™ve also known them to be traumatic. 
5 years ago, as i was getting ready to celebrate my birthday, i was struggling with deep depression after a breakup with my long-time college boyfriend. in the midst of my depression, i was sexually assaulted in the wee hours of the morning of my 23rd birthday.

when something like that happens to you, you donâ€™t know where to begin to pick up the pieces of your life. i spent so much time feeling ashamed, feeling like i had done something to convince this man that i wanted him when i didn't, feeling like i should have been more careful... the list goes on. but god! ğŸ™ŒğŸ½ the very thing that should have taken me out was the same thing that god used to draw me closer to him. though i felt so defeated at the beginning of my healing process, i realize that god was so intentional with me and that i was victorious in him. there was nothing too difficult for jesus to heal and restore. 
at that point, i made a decision to recommit my life to god fully and to let his plan lead in my life. i allowed god to heal me and show me that i was not damaged goods because of my experience.

5 years later, and i'm still standing. i'm thriving and transparent about my journey. i am absolutely an overcomer, and my voice will not be silenced!

i share my full story and the healing journey god took me on in my book the morning after prayer. 
i'm celebrating 28 so hard because i really fought hard to get here. depression almost took me out. the trauma almost took me out. but. it. didn't. god had so much more planned in store for me, and it's only the beginning!

this is to 28. and to the authentic smile in this pic because god is just so faithful! #aquarius #birthday #love #jesus #metoo #jesussaves

inhale my herb...

i'm finding me.
i'm fucking winging it. like all of us!
this is my story.
i hate being out of work. but i'm still ok being broke.

no one can make you feel what you don't want to feel! 
choices to stay absent when i was a pile of dust is seered in me.
so i sit in my loniness and found myself again.

and i know i'm proud to say i'm still learning"-#stonedagegear

text: the situations the  #metoo movement has been exposing has been going on forever in entertainment. wanda, our real life heroine, was probably no exception. in our dramatic musical there are some uncomfortable moments. our hopes as writers is that the audience will feel uncomfortable enough to understand what it is like for a woman to be dehumanized, misogynized, and taken advantage of by a man.  all these years a womanâ€™s voice was unheard, ignored, or she wasnâ€™t able to speak.  some generations just accepted it as something that happens (i know mine did). we (women) justified it and accepted it, even though inside we felt slimy, awkward and fearful in those situations. hoping to shed a little light on this in this musical, not in a political way, but in a human way.  for more info go to savagethemusical.com and stream/download our single â€œwanda savageâ€. #performingarts #musicaltheatrelife #theatrelife #actorslife #actor  #hollywood #oldhollywood #silentfilm  #entertainment #musicaltheatre #musical #broadway #broadwayshow #broadwaybound #broadwayshows #broadwayworld #broadwaymusical #newmusical #newmusicalert #womenempowerment #timesup #believewomen #womensreality #believesurvivors #everydaysexism #womenofbroadway #broadwaytheatre

text:
what iâ€™ve chosen through my high conflict divorce and co parenting ... ********************************** more often than not god calls us to do things that just do not make sense in this earthly realm. â€¢
â€œsometimes faith will make you look stupid, until it starts to rainâ€ - noah 
noah looked insane for building the ark. 
he was talked about and mocked. 
no one understood, 
but god did ! 
and when god called him into action, whether noah was going to look insane or not, he built the ark. 
noah acted on gods call and in his faith, no matter what the people around him were saying. 
iâ€™ve recognized this to be true in my walk through my divorce and co parenting situation. 
god has continued to call me to do things that honestly i can not even understand. . 
to forgive the â€œunforgivableâ€ 
to love those who continually come against you. 
to seek understanding instead of acting upon anger and hate. 
to stand in peace when there is confusion and conflict. 
i used to ask him why! 
but now i ask him, how can you use me in this

and usually that means, â€œbuckle up amie, set aside yourself and just do what god has asked, not what you feel. â€œ

like noah, i seek to act in faith, even when that means it doesnâ€™t make sense, and i am at risk of peoples judgement. 
i have chosen a daily surrender of my own thoughts and my own feelings and even the thoughts of others to pursue gods understanding and relentless love above all. 
any divorce is not easy, 
letâ€™s get realâ€”â€” neither is co parenting! 
however, when you can look to the creator of all the universe and know he has your back, 
you can step out of the way and allow god to do his thing. 
so instead of holding onto anger, bitterness, abandonment, and pain 
i choose to pursue 
understanding 
compassion 
peace 
and 
love 
and as i do so, i find my own peace, love and joy in my daily life. 
all it comes down to is a choice. 
so what will you do with it ? â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text:
f*** you medicine was deeply healing for me last year, and it's been necessary for me to revisit it now & then, so i can keep my boundaries strong(er).
.
i sat in sacred space, and let loose my anger, playing over scenes from my past that had tortured my emotions for years. my rage showed me the lessons in them & then i let loose with with screaming mental cries of f*** you to the pain, to those who'd hurt & betrayed me, to myself for being so stupid & for blaming myself. 
over & over, until i found i was repeating my mantra in a gutteral grumbles & was dizzy from how light i felt.
.
then i was silent and free.
name: R. May Evans

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

joshua green

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

#world should ever have to deal with unwelcome sexual advances 
as part of the hiring process," said charles f. coleman, jr., the

decree are designed to ensure such behavior never occurs again 
at this #restaurant." #eeoc regional attorney jeffrey burstein said, "conditioning 
hiring in exchange for #sexual favors, known as quid-pro-quo 
sexual harassment, is exactly the type of behavior that has made

harassment of this kind is eradicated from the workplace."

text:
april is recognised as sexual assault awareness month,an opportunity to educate people and raise awareness about sexual assault. sexual violence refers to crimes like sexual assault, rape, and sexual abuse. in the united states, 1 in 5 women will be raped in her lifetime,and nearly 1 in 2 women and 1 in 5 men will experience sexual violence victimisation other than rape. 
with the recent #metoo movement, sexual violence has never been such a large part of our national conversation. but what about sexual abuse victims whose abusers are not a stranger or an acquaintance? what about victims who are sexually abused by an intimate partner? our organisation will explore the intersection of domestic violence and sexual assault.
learn about marital rape and discover ways you can take a stand against domestic violence and sexual assault.
do not let anyone control you.
stand up for your ownself.
join us in putting an end to this.
#rapeisrape
#aprilrightsorganisation

text:
aviation: walking in atlanta (8/10) by nicholas jones, 01 january 2017. -

when i was walking in atlanta,
i found myself in flight amidst a night so lit with stars,
i found myself in richest history and piano bars,
looking at people through the windows of their cars,
just so i could carry their faces in my head,
when the time came for me to depart,

when i was walking in atlanta,
one man offered me the rest of his virginia slim,
with a pack stacked to the brim - on a whim,
i decided to take one more from him - just for the hell of it,
and we talked for hours about the ins and outs,
of small town life - catching flights - and counting down the minutes,
as we moved away from midnight - and what a fun night it was,

i would give just about anything in this world,
to recapture that time again - after which the memory ends,
and i find myself pulling petals from flowers,
while writing in my dream journal about what it means to fly,
from here to where i once called home,
because iâ€™ve never felt more comfortable,
than i did when i was walking down the streets,
of atlanta. -

#aviation #paralysmicpoetry #nicholasjones #poetry #prose #poetsofinstagram #poem #poet #instapoetry #quote #spilledink #instagood #depression #love #hope #blessed #soul #acceptance #spiritual #art #artistsofinstagram #introspection #writing #write #relax #anxiety #metoo #survivor #aaliyah #oneinamillion
name: The Poetry of Nicholas Jones
tweet_full:
aviation: walking in atlanta (8/10) by nicholas jones, 01 january 2017. -

when i was walking in atlanta,
i found myself in flight amidst a night so lit with stars,
i found myself in richest history and piano bars,
looking at people through the windows of their cars,
just so i could carry their faces in my head,
when the time came for me to depart,

when i was walking in atlanta,
one man offered me the rest of his virginia slim,
with a pack stacked to the brim - on a whim,
i decided to take one more from him - just for the hell of it,
and we talked for hours about the ins and outs,
of small town life - catching flights - and counting down the minutes,
as we moved away from midnight - and what a fun night it was,

i would give just about anything in this world,
to recapture that time again - after which the memory ends,
and i find myself pulling petals from flowers,
while writing in my dream journal about what it means to fly,
from here to where i once called home,
because iâ€™ve never felt more comfortable,
than i did when i was walking down the streets,
of atlanta. -

text:
some days are just like this. and some aren't. i've gotten pretty good at managing my anxiety over the years, but when life gets overwhelming my anxiety spikes...often because i feel like too much is out of my control. 
that's just it. control. if you are a survivor of trauma, like me, you have had alot of control removed from you. that's scary stuff. however, for me, the more control i surrender to god the less i struggle with my anxiety. i've chosen to not take meds, just not for me. i did for a short period, and it just wasnt right. overall what works for me is my faith, prayer, yoga, music and writing. what works for you?

some days are just like this. and some are not. i have gotten pretty good at managing my anxiety over the years, but when life gets overwhelming my anxiety spikes...often because i feel like too much is out of my control. 
that's just it. control. if you are a survivor of trauma, like me, you have had alot of control removed from you. that's scary stuff. however, for me, the more control i surrender to god the less i struggle with my anxiety. i have chosen to not take meds, just not for me. i did for a short period, and it just wasnt right. overall what works for me is my faith, prayer, yoga, music and writing. what works for you?

women should be allowed to wear what they want and when they want. they are allowed to be covered up from head to toe and only show their eyes, and they are allowed to be completely naked. 
this is what feminism is about! about letting women be who they want and when they want!! we are not our body.thick,thin,tall,short,white,black,stretch marks,acne,birth marks,scars,lesbian or trans. i do not care! we are so much more then our bodyâ€™s. 
learn the men and boys to respect women instead of telling women and girls that they should wear something that will make sure that they will be left alone by men. make sure your son does not cat call, make sure he does not touch us without our consent. make sure he learns the word no. only men who have something to hide are affraid of feminism. 
the future is female.

text:
i have become increasingly confused by the true meaning of feminism the older i get. i thought it was about equality and female empowerment. that we were fighting for a better world with no judgment or gender bias. a world where women could stop seeing each other as competition and instead love each other as kindred spirits. regardless of your life choices.
.
.
i see so much bitterness and bullying every day; fat shaming, skinny shaming, she has loose morals, is bossy, arrogant. no; she is beautiful, confident and enjoys her body, where's the harm? we need to stop being so worried about appearance and about our insecurities so we can truly find peace and equality. until then, i feel as though we are doomed...
.
.
.
.
.

the reason the movements like nazis or the new-nazis or even other extreme movements like terrorism are successful is because they know how to control the narrative. they know to tell stories that others believe. #fakenews is a good example of that. .
to bring about change, we need to control the narrative. women have been largely living in a narrative defined by the patriachical society.
.
@priyashakti is a comic book that ram devineni created, thatâ€™s been changing this narrative about women being weak, and instead paints them as powerful beings, just like the hindu goddess durga. doing this is changing the narrative about women in a country like india.
.
listen to the full interview with this amazing gentleman ram devineni! his made films while working a full time job that won awards and even recognition from the un.
.

.

text: havenâ€™t been posting much, iâ€™ve just been concentrating on getting well, but i want to talk about something really important today. please donâ€™t roll your eyes because itâ€™s a topic you hear about everywhere, it needs to be discussed by everyone who has gone through it so we can see just how prolific it is, and thatâ€™s sexual exploitation. i have always said my abuse took place at home and it was non-sexual, just physically violent and emotionally damaging. this is true about my abuse at home, but the fact is my abuse didnâ€™t end at home. i left home many times either because i was kicked out for daring to defend myself as i got older, or i would get sick of getting beat up and i would leave. but a young teenage girl is not equipped to live out in the world on her own. yesterday is the first time i ever heard the term â€œsurvival sexâ€œ. i was an extremely sexually active teenager, i also engaged in many high-risk behaviors and used drugs very regularly, particularly opiates. there were times i found myself sleeping on the couch of some random guy and they would suggest sex or coerce me into sex in exchange for a place to stay and i would give in most of the time because, when it comes down to brass tacks, i was afraid for my safety if i said no but i fooled myself into believing it was consensual. not to mention, nobody wants to sleep outside in the midst of michigan winter. i would exchange places to stay for sex pretty regularly, i recalled at least 10 or 12 situations like that last night and iâ€™m sure there were many more. one of them was incredibly threatening, he approached me in the middle of the night while i was sleeping on his basement floor. i pretended to sleep at the beginning, and then just went along with it because he was super high and huge compared to me and i was afraid. it has taken me 40 years to recognize that i was sexually exploited and in that particular situation, raped. because my physical abuse at home groomed me to believe i was the one screwing up. i was the one putting myself in bad situations. i never knew what to call that "gray area", consenting to sex that did not feel consensual. itâ€™s not gray. itâ€™s black and white. cont' in comments

text: holy smoke! what do you say to these? those of you who have been following me for a while know that i sometimes also present the work of other artists in my feed. they might have caught my attention due to their message, unusual techniques or simply colours that talk to me. these incredibly expressive dog sculptures were created by helen thompson (who works under the name â€˜holy smokeâ€™ ğŸ˜œ), an artist living in the uk. each piece is unique and handcrafted using unusual materials such as wire, natural linen and vintage textiles. the imperfections of the materials and their raw edges bring the sculptures to life and give them character. in order to give the finished pieces patina, thomson often slightly burns the edges, hence her pseudonym â€˜holy smokeâ€™. i am reminded of streetwise stray dogs. donâ€™t you think her dogs are just heartbreakingly real and fragile?

text:
i was born and brought up in the us and was lucky to have had so many privileges growing up. however, not everyone is as lucky and that is something i realized early on in life. hence, i started â€œgyaan gharâ€ learning centre at the age of 15, which is a tutoring centre located in ludhiana, punjab that provides extracurricular instructions to low-income students in new lajpat nagar. while growing up in the us, i used to arrange a fundraiser in school every year, where if each student donated 5 usd, which is somewhere around 350 indian rupees, it could help run the learning centre for an entire year! this made me realize that it doesnâ€™t take much, to just reach out and put in a little effort to help someone in some way.
we started off with 10 students and today, we have 65 students enrolled, with two full time teachers and amazing volunteers who also act like extra-curricular instructors on a daily basis. of course none of this would have been possible without my grandma who is the de facto principal of â€œgyaan gharâ€ and oversees the daily functioning of the centre. even at the age of 80, she does it with so much gusto and enthusiasm! it is her commitment to creating a change in the community that drives me to do the same as well.
after completing my graduation in economics from harvard, i permanently moved to india to work with aangan india, which is a non-profit organization dedicated to reducing child harm in the forms of trafficking, early marriage, labour, and violence. i have a deeply personal passion for working on making women and children safer. especially with the #metoo movement all around us, it feels really important to lend a voice to those who may not even have the visibility to say 'me too.â€™ i believe that those of us who are lucky enough to be born with privilege have a responsibility to lift others up with us.
#kindnessunlimited
- ratna gill @aangan_trust
name: Kindness Unlimited

after completing my graduation in economics from harvard, i permanently moved to india to work with aangan india, which is a non-profit organization dedicated to reducing child harm in the forms of trafficking, early marriage, labour, and violence. i have a deeply personal passion for working on making women and children safer. especially with the #metoo movement all around us, it feels really important to lend a voice to those who may not even have the visibility to say 'me too.â€™ i believe that those of us who are lucky enough to be born with privilege have a responsibility to lift others up with us.
#kindnessunlimited
- ratna gill @aangan_trust

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican pay was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

.

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
when a project is constructed around nudity and equated with freedom, does a woman who chooses not to disrobe for any reason then live in permanent unfreedom? how does one photograph women naked and interpret that as â€œpowerâ€ when women in india, especially dalit and adivasi, are regularly stripped as punishment?

#metoo isn't just about harassment/direct sexual violence and shouldn't be reduced to that. there are other forms of violence and harassment that occupy the dominant ways in which scholarship, art, technology is produced. our second essay on #metoo takes apart the ethics of photography as they exist in india and internationally. when we contacted people for this piece, they literally began pulling images off their websites. details when you read.

this piece has spent a long time in post-production where our editorial team has debated the use of images, consent and despaired deeply about the state of photography as an art in india. we are blessed to have such wonderful people who spoke to us - some anonymously and others openly - to help us bring a discussion of ethics in photography to a wider audience. a huge thank you to everyone who has collaborated with us on the writing of this piece written by @suchitravijayan 
@herdsceneand

a united states rapper, singer, songwriter from the bronx, new york city who just became the first female solo artist in the history of the grammy awards to win the award for best rap album. her accomplishment marks an important moment within her music genre (a notoriously male dominated and overtly misogynistic arena) as well as more broadly across popular music widely criticized for its misogyny to this day.  cardiâ€™s win stands testament not only her own work as an artist, but to the work of female artists worldwide and throughout herstory, whose creations challenge stereotypes and occupy space despite the direct, cultural, and structural violence working to silence them

text: part 1... sex offender registries identify convicted sex offenders that may be residing in your community. you can search using various criteria including the sex offender's name, gender, race, and address. you can also perform a broader search to identify the number of sex offenders within a given county, city or zip code. the registry also provides a photo of the offender so you will know them if you see them. two additional pieces of information provided are their registry classification (i.e. - sex offender, sexually dangerous predator, absconder) and the type of crime they committed. have you viewed the registry for your community? if so, what did you learn and how did you feel about it? #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #super bowl

offenses such as rape, domestic violence and stalking will be severely punished as of wednesday. up until now, the minimum serving time for such crimes was 6 months and convicted criminals often got away with parole. even chancellor sebastian kurz commented on the matter saying â€œwhen minor white-collar crime is punished more harshly in austria than violence against women and children, which often results in lifelong psychological and physical damage, then something is very wrong. we now seek to correct that.â€ sentences will now be raised to 1-10 years. change is coming! what do you think? #dontbeastranger

sounds great but how?
those layers of shit that dimmed your fucking shine have a tendency to build up. 
layer on layer and we wonder, 
if itâ€™s even possible to get out from under the weights
it totally is possible

you know what worked?
connection.  the only difference between the women who can sidestep the layers and shine and the ones who keep adding layers of evidence that it wonâ€™t work- again?
second chakra work. 
just try this today- rather than listen for a place to respond in conversations just listen to connect.  rather than think we know where someone is headed with a conversation, listen to connect. 
your hearts are already connected.  just like metronomes we beat in sync with who we are around

text:
it was indeed an awesome and eye-opening session at the 3rd edition of who's that girl 2019 @wtg_nigeria . our managing partner mr adesanmi adebunmi @imentorsanmi joined mrs oyinda ige ceo of @the_nest_creche , mrs adenike babalola ceo ofÂ  @denikechips and mr jibril abdulrahim a consultant psychiatrist, uch in giving the young boys a charge to treat all the ladies as queens that they truly are. also in attendance was mrs funsho adegbola director, the vale college @thevalecollege

enough is enough with rape, sexual assaults and abuse. we need to raise a generation of men who from being young boys are made to understand that there's no strength in 'overpowering' a lady; there's no strength in being a bully and it's time we made them know that no simply means no. 
kudos to mrs ronke giwa-onafuwa @ronkegiwa1 for this laudable project and congratulations for a hugely successful 3rd edition 'who's that girl', 2019. next edition will be even better and greater. 
#wtg #risconsult #nomeansno #notosexualabuse #girl #metoo
#queens

text:
learn how #advocate can help your institution manage student misconduct. 
student misconduct cases that are related to campus safety and sexual misconduct hit the headlines more frequently since the #metoo movement started. authorities and the general public take a more critical voice when incidents occur on campus. whilst universities doing their best to support students and handling cases, often the challenges are within processes and systems, especially around data management and reporting. here is what our clients have been seeing since using symplicity advocate: 85% increased efficiency in tracking conduct cases 80% of user confirmed it helped with compliance 90% faster reporting 50% better prevention 10% higher audit accuracy 30% better internal, interdepartmental communication find out more about our solutions for student services in our upcoming online webinar: webinar, 14 feb, 1pm - addressing case management, campus security, compliance & prevention.

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,Â wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:

todayâ€™s #musicmonday is one that is deeply personal to me - and a source of great humility and pride. working for the past 10 years with #makemusicmatter has been a roller coaster to say the least. but today i can honestly say that we have something special going on. todayâ€™s song is an example of the power that music has to heal the soul. 
sandra was a participant in our flagship #healinginharmony program at the panzi hospital in the democratic republic of congo. through the program she was able to tell her story - in her own words - through song. the experience transformed her - and all participants into artists. not victims. artists. it is people like her that make the past 10 years of challenges worth it. so today i honour her journey and that of all the people involved in making this crazy dream come true.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text_retweet:
reposted from @shesurvived_ -  when i met him over the course of our relationship i saw parts of myself that i valued so much start to slowly disappear. gradually i turned into someone i didn't recognize.

i was always paranoid, nervous and anxious without any explanation. i found myself worrying about if he saw me accidently looking at a guy as i walk, or if he finds out i spoke to a male group member in college. i was too scared to talk, in case i hurt his feelings. i had lost myself and didn't realize until it was too late.
this was one of many attacks.. leading upto it i chose to ignore all the warning signs. clenched fists. punching walls. slamming doors and smashing glasses. truth is i was used to this behavior and i didn't question it like i should have.

that day i remember his temper and paranoia increased as i became non existent. he took my phone in anger to see who'd been texting me, determined to find some kind of evidence of infidelity. he was so adamant in finding something, anything just to have one on me.

he finally returned, convinced i must have deleted all the messages. so he smashed my phone and grabbed me, gripped firmly around my neck, squeezing with all his strength he held onto my throat.
i didnâ€™t know what he was saying when he was screaming at me, i can't even remember what i was thinking. all i remember was the complete and utter shock and terror i felt in my stomach, as i looked into the eyes of someone i loved and felt for a moment that there was a chance that he could have killed me.

i was numb after with him crying, apologising andÂ begging for forgiveness. i never wanted to see him again. i could no longer look him in the eyes. the time he strangled me should have been my wakeup call, but what did i do? 
i forgave him. 
the cycle continued... #abuse#saynotoabuse#domesticviolence#fear#pain#attack#scared#survivor#shesurvived#silent#suffer  #domesticviolence #domesticviolenceawarenessmonth #survivor #domesticviolenceawareness #domesticabuse #awareness #dvam #metoo #dustingoffdomesticviolence #endthestereotype #domesticviolencesurvivor #dvam2018 #purplethursday #breakthesilence #abusesurvivor #narcissisticabuse #believesurvivors #

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
likeability penaltyâ€ is a term coined by sheryl sandberg, facebookâ€™s chief operating officer and founder of the lean in foundation. it reflects how women in business are penalised when exhibiting qualities usually attributed to their male counterparts. that is, in a leadership position â€“ one of authority, respect and high achievement â€“ behaviours that are admirable in men, are viewed less favourably in women, or even disliked.
leadership roles require self-assertion, decisiveness, passion, a proactive approach and confidence in oneâ€™s skill and ability, which are viewed as positive attributes in male colleagues. however, these qualities tend to be viewed negatively when demonstrated by female leaders.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur
