text:
you. have to suffer to grow. thats what i believe. i was scared of so many things in my life but know what? i faced them and still do because everything you're running from is simply the truth â˜ğŸ½ i suffered. i've been trough hell. i'd blame everyone and everything around me - my whole life. everyday was about being accepted by others. i wanted them to like me. 
today i know that was a gift. my childhood was a gift. my loneliness was a gift. my insecurity was a gift. the fact that no one helped me was a gift. everything - even when life knocked me down was a gift â˜ğŸ½ when i got called, i fell "asleep" for three days. i'm trying not to think of it but when i do i feel like something forces me to my knees. at this point i realized that a human being is not so human anymore. "we have the ability to go in such a space if you're willing to suffer - and i mean suffer your brain - your body - once they connect you are able to do anything!" that evening - two years ago - changed my whole life. i was on the brick of death. it wasn't about others, it wasn't about my future, about my past, about the shitty people, about anything. it became a personal thing. i came up as a person living "the outside" and found my drive and my strengh by living "the inside" â˜ğŸ½ you have to believe in yourself my love. you have to believe in simply everything.

text:
being an independent woman means you speak your mind. you call people out when they start treating you like shit, even if that means youâ€™ll risk being called crazy or psycho or bitchy. when someone disrespects you, you donâ€™t let them get away with it, because you know what you deserve.
being an independent woman means you support other women. you donâ€™t view them as your competition. you donâ€™t judge them based on what they are wearing or what career they are pursuing. you hand them tampons in bathrooms. you compliment their hair. you help them get home safely. you treat other women as your teammates.
being an independent woman means you never keep toxic people in your world for long. you cut them out as soon as possible, because you know you are strong enough to survive without them. you donâ€™t need their negativity weighing you down. you donâ€™t need to make living more stressful than it already is.
being an independent woman means you are comfortable within the walls of your skin. maybe you step out of the house in sweats or maybe you prefer skintight skirts, but either way, you feel confident wearing them. you love yourself and love your body, because it does so much for you.
even when you are an independent woman, there will still be days when you feel lonely. there will still be times when you wish you were in a relationship because you are sick of the single life. and there is nothing wrong with that.
you can be in a loving relationship and be an independent woman. you can ask for help and be an independent woman. you can feel insecure on certain days and be an independent woman. you can daydream about getting married and having babies and be an independent woman.
your independence doesnâ€™t depend on your relationship status. it depends on your strength. on your energy. on how much you accomplish in a day.

being an independent woman means you speak your mind. you call people out when they start treating you like shit, even if that means youâ€™ll risk being called crazy or psycho or bitchy. when someone disrespects you, you donâ€™t let them get away with it, because you know what you deserve.
being an independent woman means you support other women. you donâ€™t view them as your competition. you donâ€™t judge them based on what they are wearing or what career they are pursuing. you hand them tampons in bathrooms. you compliment their hair. you help them get home safely. you treat other women as your teammates.
being an independent woman means you never keep toxic people in your world for long. you cut them out as soon as possible, because you know you are strong enough to survive without them. you donâ€™t need their negativity weighing you down. you donâ€™t need to make living more stressful than it already is.
being an independent woman means you are comfortable within the walls of your skin. maybe you step out of the house in sweats or maybe you prefer skintight skirts, but either way, you feel confident wearing them. you love yourself and love your body, because it does so much for you.
even when you are an independent woman, there will still be days when you feel lonely. there will still be times when you wish you were in a relationship because you are sick of the single life. and there is nothing wrong with that.
you can be in a loving relationship and be an independent woman. you can ask for help and be an independent woman. you can feel insecure on certain days and be an independent woman. you can daydream about getting married and having babies and be an independent woman.
your independence doesnâ€™t depend on your relationship status. it depends on your strength. on your energy. on how much you accomplish in a day.

i went to see matilda in the west end yesterday. matilda is a little girl who has very unfortunate circumstances. she comes from a home where she's not loved or cared for. many people who come from a home like that end up putting up with people mistreating them later in life too. i'd encourage you today to really take a look at your relationships and if someone is treating you unfairly, remember, you don't have to just grin and bear it. speak up, seek out some help and support if you need to, but decide for yourself that you'll only spend time with someone who treats you well.

a new anxiety trait has come out of it though, extreme nausea. iâ€™ve often feel sick in my stomach when iâ€™m anxious but this is from my throat if that makes sense? like iâ€™m about to gag. 
i havenâ€™t been able to go to work or class, iâ€™ve been quit paralysed but this. but i have to remember what happened to my friends is a lot in addition to what happened to me. this is a normal reaction! so for the first time iâ€™ve kinda been able to give myself a break about feeling down.

10 reasons why you should have a major #fomo if you havenâ€™t attended #lahootimelo this year? 
1. youâ€™ve majorly missed a great lineup and such impressive talks
2. lahooti made everyone to take something great, back home with them
3. lahooti forced everyone including audience, speakers, critics, thinkers and media to look for solutions for so many burning questions like oppression, fanaticism, education, empowerment, creative expressions, inclusion, tolerance, etc.
4. music was absolutely on point! introducing edm to public is no joke. seeing the audienceâ€™s glee and amusement was a thriller in itself
5. gender balanced panels and performances - definitely other festival organisers must learn something from this 
6. if there were only 20% women in the audience on the first day then it became at least 40% on the second day - clearly tells so much more about the atmosphere 
7. there was absolutely no judgementtttt! 
8. audience was madly respectful towards women - raising bars for sindh
9. top-notch security 
10. sindhâ€™s audience deserves a massive shout out for being so well-behaved. they queued up properly to enter the venue. they followed the security protocol for everyoneâ€™s safety. this definitely tells so much about sindhâ€™s people

credit for creating and curating such an awesomeness filled weekend goes to @saifsamejo and @sanakhoja. standing ovation.

ps. more pictures and videos will follow in coming posts and stories

text:
~ "guardian angel"  a poem
Â·
violated by the hands of a sexual deviant
Â·
those eyes...good to evil in mere seconds
Â· 
sleepless nights merge seamlessly into restless days
Â·
each one blending into the next, without fail
Â·
what day is it?
Â·
i see his face when i close my eyes
Â·
how long until that goes away? 
never?
Â·
going anywhere alone is out of the question...but for how long?
Â·
too many friends to count, i'm always there for them
Â·
i'm here...struggling. where are they?
Â·
why am i here, suffering...alone with my horrified thoughts?
Â·
the late afternoon sun beaming radiantly through the blinds
Â·
my sleepy eyes staring at the wall as if in a trance
Â·
shapes of light slowly evolving as the sun declines
Â·
a ghostly figure appears before my eyes
Â·
my guardian angel, perhaps?
Â·
is this all i need to watch over me?
Â·
no...
Â·
Â·

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

text:
what is the blueprint for life?
what arrangement of decisions, feelings and choices make up the perfect life?

now they are two hell of a questions to ask yourself on a monday morning right? ğŸ‘€

when we are children we are absolutely dependent. if not we wouldn't last very long.

but in that innocent weakness, there lies an immense strength. to get up over and over again after we have fallen. to persist. to believe it can happen.

we have been programmed for resilience since we were children. 
if you feel weak and hopeless then take a think back. 
your very foundations are immensely powerful. âœŠ
